AdvertisementBut capping what students can borrow would exacerbate rather than ease the class tensions that already dominate higher education.
Middle-income families eager to keep up, however, would end up taking on much more costly private student loans to fill the gap created by the caps.
But for the vast majority of the higher education student body – undergrad degree-seekers at public universities – a cap on lending wouldn’t shift prices at all.
But none of these approaches to the balance of costs and debt for future learners will do anything for the 45 million people who already owe $1.5 trillion on student loans.
Big ideas for tackling the existing debt crisis are unlikely to attach to the Higher Education Act legislative process, however.